<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8427&amp;p=87808#p87808"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Which color palette is the most fun to use?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8427&amp;p=87808#p87808"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />A problem with HSL is that, despite its friendliness to art designers, it's not well suited for use at runtime in any environment that has to implement gel (colored lighting) or translucency<br /></div><br />SNES supports transparency in hardware.<br />About lightning, HSL is better than RGB as you can do various kinds of effects by addning some bias to the L values, and it'll look overall better than adding some bias to individual R, G and B components.<br /><br />Also you can do saturation effects (for example if something colored is turned to stone you can do it "smoothly" or hue effects (if you want something to change it's color gradually, it'll be extremely simple as opposed to the complex calculation it'd be in RGB).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=38">Bregalad</a> — Wed Dec 21, 2011 2:03 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
